&lt;p>The old (left in this picture) and new boundary stones, marked A, B and EPB as above.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The Welstor Newtake wall behind was built in 1771 to enclose open moorland for grazing. We keep it on our left all the way to Buckland Beacon.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Historically, on Dartmoor, &amp;ldquo;newtakes&amp;rdquo; were enclosures of common land for agricultural purposes, and also to exclude others from grazing it. This practice often led to conflict between commoners who held rights over the land, and the landowners who erected these walls.&lt;/p>
